## Diagnosis

The symptom — active label appearing on the **right** side while hover labels sit on the **left** — is a classic **coordinate-space mismatch** combined with a **transform-origin / translation direction error**.

### What's happening

ScrollSpy labels are almost certainly positioned with something like:

```css
left: 100%;          /* pushes label RIGHT of the anchor */
transform: translateX(8px);
```

…while the hover labels use:

```css
right: 100%;         /* pulls label LEFT of the anchor */
transform: translateX(-8px);
```

When you "fixed the anchor" from the tick to the notch container, the *offset* changed but the *direction* did not — so the label moved but still went right. That's why you saw no meaningful improvement.

The secondary issue is that `position: absolute` on the label resolves against whichever ancestor has `position: relative` **first**. If the notch container doesn't establish its own stacking context, the label may be resolving against the viewport or a higher wrapper, which explains the viewport-edge overflow.

**Anti-pattern: AP-072** — positional anchor switched without inverting the translation axis.

---

## Root Cause

Two things together:

1. **Wrong side**: `left: 100%` (or equivalent positive `translateX`) pushes the label rightward. The gutter sits on the left, so the label needs `right: 100%`.
2. **Wrong containing block**: The label's `position: absolute` isn't resolving against the notch element because the notch (or its parent) doesn't have `position: relative` set — so the browser walks up the tree until it finds one, landing on a wider container that lets the label escape the viewport.

---

## Fix

### 1. Locate the ScrollSpy component

```
components/ui/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpy.tsx          # or .jsx
components/ui/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpyItem.tsx
```

### 2. Ensure the notch container establishes a containing block

```tsx
// ScrollSpyItem.tsx  (or wherever the notch/tick is rendered)

// BEFORE — notch probably has no position, or position:absolute without relative parent
<div className="scroll-spy-notch">
  <span className="scroll-spy-tick" />
  {isActive && <ActiveLabel text={label} />}
</div>

// AFTER — add `relative` so the label resolves HERE
<div className="scroll-spy-notch relative">   {/* ← key addition */}
  <span className="scroll-spy-tick" />
  {isActive && <ActiveLabel text={label} />}
</div>
```

### 3. Invert the label's anchor direction

```tsx
// ActiveLabel.tsx  (or inline in ScrollSpyItem)

// BEFORE
<span
  className="
    absolute
    left-full          // ← this is the culprit; pushes RIGHT
    top-1/2
    -translate-y-1/2
    translate-x-2
    whitespace-nowrap
    text-sm font-medium
  "
>
  {text}
</span>

// AFTER — mirror to match the hover-label gutter (left side)
<span
  className="
    absolute
    right-full         // ← pulls label LEFT of the notch
    top-1/2
    -translate-y-1/2
    -translate-x-2     // ← gap now opens leftward
    whitespace-nowrap
    text-sm font-medium
    text-right         // ← keeps text flush with the rail edge
  "
>
  {text}
</span>
```

### 4. Verify hover labels use the identical position values

Open whatever renders the hover tooltip and confirm it is **already** using `right-full`. If it uses a CSS class rather than Tailwind, do the same inversion in the stylesheet:

```css
/* scrollspy.css – if you're not using Tailwind for this */

/* BEFORE */
.scroll-spy-active-label {
  left: 100%;
  transform: translateY(-50%) translateX(8px);
}

/* AFTER */
.scroll-spy-active-label {
  right: 100%;
  transform: translateY(-50%) translateX(-8px);
  text-align: right;           /* keeps text right-aligned toward the rail */
}

/* Confirm hover label matches exactly */
.scroll-spy-hover-label {
  right: 100%;
  transform: translateY(-50%) translateX(-8px);
  text-align: right;
}
```

### 5. (Optional but clean) Extract to a shared label utility class

Since both the hover and active labels should be **identical** in placement, de-duplicate:

```css
/* tokens/scrollspy.css */
.spy-rail-label {
  position: absolute;
  right: 100%;
  top: 50%;
  transform: translateY(-50%) translateX(-0.5rem);
  white-space: nowrap;
  text-align: right;
}
```

```tsx
// Use everywhere
<span className="spy-rail-label">{text}</span>
```

---

## Checklist before shipping

```
[ ] notch wrapper has `position: relative` (or Tailwind `relative`)
[ ] active label uses `right-full` / `right: 100%`
[ ] active label translateX is NEGATIVE (opens gap leftward)
[ ] hover label and active label share the same positioning class
[ ] no parent container clips overflow in the left direction
    (check for `overflow-hidden` on the rail or sidebar wrapper)
[ ] viewport-edge overflow is gone at all breakpoints
```

---

## Principle

> **Positional symmetry must be enforced at the axis level, not just the anchor level.**  
> Switching the anchor element without inverting `left↔right` and `+offset↔−offset` is a no-op in appearance. The containing-block chain must be audited at the same time, because an element with `position: absolute` silently re-parents itself to the nearest positioned ancestor — which may not be the element you intend.
